title: The reaction 19F(d,n)20Ne.

x4freetext: The reaction 19F(d,n)20Ne.

x4codes.hlp: Rice University, Houston, TX, United States of America

x4freetext: The deuteron bombarding energy is known to an accuracy
of better than 2%.The beam was integrated in a current
integrator with an absolute accuracy of +-3% and, in
addition, a long counter placed at 90 degr. was used to
monitor the neutron yield.
Neutrons were detected in a large (12.5 cm
diameter*2.5 cm) encapsulated liquid scintillator NE213
viewed by a Philips 58 AVP photomultiplier. The
measurement of the absolute cross section was performed
with a 4 cm diameter*2.5 cm stilbene detector and a 56
AVP phototube.
Both CaF2 and PbF2 targets were used. The PbF2 targets
were produced by etching 1 mm thick lead discs with
fluoric acid; however, these targets proved to be
rather inhomogeneous. Better results were obtained by
evaporating several layers of CaF2 onto a 0.1 mm thick
gold backing.The thickness of the targets used varied
between 80 keV and 100 keV for 1.5 MeV protons, as
determined from the broadening of the 1.38MeV resonance
of the 19F(p,ag)16O reaction. In addition the
evaporated targets were weighed. Both measurements of
target thickness agreed within 10%. The targets were
contained in a cylindrical cup with 0.3 mm thick
aluminium walls,which also acted as a Faraday cup.
The relative yields of the neutron groups and the
yields at different deuteron energies having been
corrected for neutron detection efficiency, solid angle
variations,different target thickness,bias settings and
accumulated charge.
The error in relative cross section of different
neutron groups due to uncertainties in counter
efficiency and incomplete resolution is estimated to be
smaller than +-20%; the relative error in the
differential cross section between forward and backward
angles due to the same effects is smaller than +-10%.
The relative cross section for different deuteron
energies are believed to be correct within +-15%.
The angular resolution was +- 1.2 degr. for the flight
path of 3 m and less for the longer paths.
The accuracy of the angle settings was +-1.5 degr.
